i## Problem		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iI frequently encounter the situation that the Pipewire audio server is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isuddenly stopped:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- The problem usually appears when I connect/disconnect my laptop from		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  the power adapter. My computer usually lags for a short time while		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  switching between performance profiles.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `systemctl --user status pipewire.service` only shows that the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Pipewire process was terminated by a `SIGKILL` signal, without any		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  other useful log information.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Neither `coredumpctl` nor `dmesg` shows the existence of a core dump		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  event.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Cause		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe Pipewire process runs with realtime priority, with which its		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ischeduling needs are satisfied first, so it can process audio data in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itime to prevent stuttering. To increase its process priority, Pipewire		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iuses its `libpipewire-module-rt` module to send requests to the `RTKit`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iservice running as `root` in the system. `RTKit` then changes process		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipriority with its privileges.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, if a process with realtime priority encountered a bug, for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iexample an infinite loop, it will consume all CPU resources. Since		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imost of the other processes (including but not limited to, SSH daemon,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iXorg, and your shell) are running with a lower priority, they won't		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iget any CPU time slices, and won't be able to handle any tasks,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iincluding your command inputs trying to fix the system.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTo mitigate this problem, Linux kernel limits the execution time of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irealtime processes by default. Under the default settings, a realtime		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprocess must finish its computations (like Pipewire's audio		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprocessing) within 200ms, and use the `sched_yield` system call to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ireturn CPU time slices to other processes. It can then wait for the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
inext event in the background (like running out of audio buffer on the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isound card), when Linux kernel invokes this process again. If the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irealtime process does not finish within 200ms, Linux kernel will send		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ia SIGKILL signal to terminate the process.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBecause my computer was lagging while switching between performance		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprofiles, Pipewire spent more than 200ms on handling audio data, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithus was terminated by Linux kernel.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Solution		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince I'm unable to fix the lagging while switching performance		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprofiles, I decided to increase Pipewire's time limit to 5 seconds,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ienough for it to process audio data even when the computer is lagging.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFirst we need to change the settings for Pipewire's `libpipewire-module-rt`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imodule, to make it request a longer time limit:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    "context.modules": [		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        "args": {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          "nice.level": -11,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          "rt.prio": 88,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          "rt.time.hard": 5000000,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          "rt.time.soft": 5000000		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        },		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        "flags": ["ifexists", "nofail"],		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        "name": "libpipewire-module-rt"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    ]		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe unit for 5000000 is microseconds. Pipewire will now request a 5		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isecond time limit.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThen, since `RTKit` imposes an additional layer of execution time		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilimit, we need to add a startup argument to `RTKit` to increase that		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilimit as well. Run `systemctl edit rtkit-daemon.service` , and enter		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe following config:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  [Service]		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # First, clear the original ExecStart command.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ExecStart=		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Then replace with our command with additional arguments.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # If your distro puts rtkit-daemon elsewhere, change command to match.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ExecStart=/usr/lib/rtkit-daemon --rttime-usec-max=5000000		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you're using NixOS, you can use the following config instead:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  let		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    # Time limit in microseconds		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    realtimeLimitUS = 5000000;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  in {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    security.rtkit.enable = true;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    systemd.services.rtkit-daemon.serviceConfig.ExecStart = [		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      "" # Override command in rtkit package's service file		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      "${pkgs.rtkit}/libexec/rtkit-daemon --rttime-usec-max=${builtins.toString realtimeLimitUS}"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    ];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    services.pipewire.enable = true;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    environment.etc = {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      "pipewire/pipewire.conf.d/rtprio.conf".text = builtins.toJSON {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        "context.modules" = [		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            name = "libpipewire-module-rt";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            args = {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              "nice.level" = -11;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              "rt.prio" = 88;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              "rt.time.soft" = realtimeLimitUS;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              "rt.time.hard" = realtimeLimitUS;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            flags = ["ifexists" "nofail"];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        ];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}